---
import Layout from "@/components/Layout.astro";
import { meta } from "@/lib/load";
import { formatDate } from "@/lib/format";
import { withBase } from "@/lib/paths";

const c = meta.counts;
const corpusStart = meta.corpusStart ? formatDate(meta.corpusStart) : "11 November 2025";
---

<Layout title="About">
  <div class="page about prose stack">
    <h1>About this tracker</h1>
    <p class="lede">
      Under the Policy for the responsible use of AI in government, Commonwealth
      agencies have had to publish AI transparency statements since February 2025.
      This project keeps a faithful, dated record of those statements and makes
      the changes legible.
    </p>

    <h2>How it works</h2>
    <p>
      Every day, an automated program visits each agency&rsquo;s statement, saves a
      copy, and notes anything that has changed since the day before. Over time this
      builds a complete, dated history of how every statement has evolved, down to
      the wording. This site presents that history &mdash; it adds no commentary of
      its own beyond the analysis described below.
    </p>

    <h2>Origins</h2>
    <p>
      This tracker began in the audience. As Senator Katy Gallagher launched the
      Australian Public Service&rsquo;s AI Plan on {corpusStart}, Ben Swift opened a
      laptop and started archiving the agencies&rsquo; transparency statements then and
      there. That is why the record opens when it does, and why the statements&rsquo;
      first nine months, before the project was watching, fall outside it. What that
      start point means for the figures is set out in <a
        href={withBase("/reading#corpus")}>how to read the data</a
      >.
    </p>

    <h2>Methodology</h2>
    <p>
      For a plain-language guide to what the scores and colours on this site mean,
      and what they don&rsquo;t, see <a href={withBase("/reading")}>how to read the
      data</a>. The notes here are the technical method behind them.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>Timeline.</strong> Each change is read straight from git. Spurious
        scrape churn that is later reverted, and pure reformatting, are collapsed
        out; commits the maintainer flagged as noise are hidden by default. Bulk
        imports are shown as &ldquo;first tracked&rdquo; rather than
        &ldquo;published&rdquo;, since we don&rsquo;t know the true publication date.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Propagation</strong> is detected lexically: passages are normalised
        (links, markup, punctuation and case removed) and matched across agencies,
        with a separate pass for canonical template phrases. We only assert that a
        passage co-occurs across statements &mdash; never who copied whom &mdash;
        though passages also found in the DTA&rsquo;s own statement are marked.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Originality</strong> is the share of a statement&rsquo;s text (by
        length) that is <em>not</em> shared with other agencies or drawn from
        template language. The DTA scores low because it is the template source, so
        it is labelled accordingly.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Similarity</strong> uses OpenAI <code>text-embedding-3-small</code>
        vectors and cosine distance. Embeddings are cached by content hash, so a
        statement is only re-embedded when its text changes.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Related work</h2>
    <p>
      Plenty of people study these statements; as far as we know, nobody else
      tracks how they <em>change</em>. The first systematic analysis of the
      Australian corpus &mdash; <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2604.26075">Pan
      et al. (2026)</a>, who assembled the <em>AITS-101</em> dataset &mdash; and
      an <a
        href="https://www.admscentre.org.au/government-ai-transparency-statements-hard-to-find-new-report-finds/"
        >audit by the ADM+S Centre</a
      > both read the statements as a single snapshot. The Digital
      Transformation Agency&rsquo;s <a
        href="https://www.dta.gov.au/articles/new-central-register-ai-transparency-statements-commonwealth-entities"
        >central register</a
      > aspires to surface major updates but publishes no version history. The
      missing time axis is what this project adds.
    </p>
    <p>
      The method is borrowed rather than invented. Longitudinal corpora of
      privacy policies &mdash; notably the <a
        href="https://privacypolicies.cs.princeton.edu/">Princeton&ndash;Leuven
        corpus</a
      > &mdash; and terms-of-service trackers have long committed each snapshot
      to git and diffed it; we point the same technique at government AI
      transparency statements. The nearest efforts abroad track AI <em>use</em>
      rather than the statements themselves &mdash; registers like the
      UK&rsquo;s <a
        href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/algorithmic-transparency-recording-standard-hub"
        >Algorithmic Transparency Recording Standard</a
      > and the Amsterdam and Helsinki algorithm registers &mdash; or score
      transparency over time, like Stanford&rsquo;s <a
        href="https://news.stanford.edu/stories/2025/12/foundation-model-transparency-index-ai-companies-information"
        >Foundation Model Transparency Index</a
      >. None diffs the text of agency statements.
    </p>

    <h2>Caveats</h2>
    <p>
      Scraping is imperfect: site redesigns, bot-blocks and PDF extraction can
      introduce noise, and the coverage classification (published / not yet /
      exempt) is a best-effort reading of each agency&rsquo;s obligations. Treat the
      figures as indicative, and follow the source link on any statement to check
      the original.
    </p>

    <h2>Credits</h2>
    <p>
      This tracker is a <a
        href="https://cybernetics.anu.edu.au/cybernetic-studio/"
        >Cybernetic Studio</a
      > project created by <a href="https://benswift.me">Dr Ben Swift</a> at the <a
        href="https://cybernetics.anu.edu.au">ANU School of Cybernetics</a
      >.
    </p>

    <h2>Citation and referencing</h2>
    <p>
      This tracker is archived on Zenodo with a permanent DOI, and Ben Swift is its
      sole creator and maintainer. If the project, its data or its analysis is
      useful to you, a citation or credit is appreciated &mdash; it also helps
      others find the source and check it for themselves.
    </p>
    <p>
      The DOI <a href="https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.20842437"
        ><code>10.5281/zenodo.20842437</code></a
      > is a <em>concept</em> DOI: it always resolves to the latest archived
      version, so a citation never goes stale as this living work gains new
      releases.
    </p>
    <p><strong>In scholarly work</strong>, cite it as:</p>
    <blockquote class="about__cite">
      Swift, B. (2025). <cite>Australian Government AI Transparency Tracker</cite>
      [Software]. ANU School of Cybernetics. <a
        href="https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.20842437"
        >https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.20842437</a
      >
    </blockquote>
    <p>
      A machine-readable <a
        href="https://github.com/ANUcybernetics/aps-ai-transparency-tracker/blob/main/CITATION.cff"
        ><code>CITATION.cff</code></a
      > in the repository can generate the equivalent BibTeX or other formats, and
      the Zenodo record exports them directly.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>In a newspaper, blog or other non-academic piece</strong>, a plain
      credit with a link is all that&rsquo;s needed &mdash; for example:
    </p>
    <blockquote class="about__cite">
      Data from the <a href={withBase("/")}>Australian Government AI Transparency
        Tracker</a>, a project by Dr Ben Swift at the ANU School of Cybernetics.
    </blockquote>
    <p>
      Please link to this site rather than only naming it, so readers can reach the
      underlying record. When you quote a figure, a date is worth including: the
      corpus is updated daily, so the numbers move.
    </p>

    <h2>Licensing</h2>
    <p>
      The scraper and this site are released under the MIT License. The statement
      text belongs to the respective agencies; most Australian Government content is
      licensed CC BY 4.0, but check each agency&rsquo;s site for specifics.
    </p>

    <p class="muted about__build">
      {c.statements} statements, {c.revisions} tracked changes, {c.embedded} embedded.
      Built {formatDate(meta.builtAt)} from {meta.headSha.slice(0, 7)}.
    </p>
  </div>
</Layout>

<style>
  .about {
    max-width: 46rem;
  }

  .about__cite {
    margin-block: var(--space-3);
    padding-inline-start: var(--space-3);
    border-inline-start: 1px solid var(--border);
    color: var(--muted);
  }

  .about__cite cite {
    font-style: italic;
  }

  .about__build {
    margin-block-start: var(--space-6);
    padding-block-start: var(--space-3);
    border-top: 1px solid var(--border);
    font-size: 0.85rem;
  }
</style>
